---
description: Docker, CI/CD, and deployment rules
globs: .github/**, docker-compose*, Dockerfile, backend/Dockerfile, frontend/Dockerfile
---

Deployment stack:
- Docker for packaging (multi-stage builds for both frontend and backend).
- Docker Compose for local development (PostgreSQL, Redis, backend, frontend).
- GitHub Actions for CI (lint, test, build validation).
- Docker Compose prod variant for production-like deployments.

DevOps rules:
- Applications must be container-friendly and stateless where possible.
- Keep builds reproducible; use environment-driven configuration.
- Separate build-time config from runtime config.
- Add health checks for API and workers; ensure logs are structured and production-usable.
- Support observability: system logs, AI monitoring, latency, error tracking.

Docker expectations:
- Keep Dockerfiles clean and optimized; use multi-stage builds.
- Avoid baking secrets into images; minimize image size.
- Use .dockerignore to exclude node_modules, .next, .git, etc.

CI/CD expectations (GitHub Actions):
- Run lint (ruff, ESLint), tests (pytest, vitest), and build validation before merge.
- Use FORCE_JAVASCRIPT_ACTIONS_TO_NODE24 for GitHub Actions Node.js compatibility.
- Keep deployment config version-controlled.
- Separate environments: dev (docker-compose.yml), prod (docker-compose.prod.yml).

Local development:
- docker-compose.yml defines: postgres, redis, backend, frontend.
- PostgreSQL on port 5433 (mapped from 5432), Redis on port 6380 (mapped from 6379).
- Backend on port 8000, Frontend on port 3000.

Do not:
- Hardcode database URLs, Redis URLs, or API keys in Docker configs.
- Mix deployment-only hacks into application logic.
- Assume local-only paths or config in production code.
